{
  "text": "There was a significant main effect of maternal diet on neonatal weight from P1-P21 (P < 0.05, Supplemental Figure 2A ). Female offspring born to UN dams were significantly lighter at birth compared to those of control pregnancies (P < 0.0001, Supplemental Figure 2B ), consistent with our previous data [CITATION_1] . Maternal UN did not affect the number of live pups delivered per litter (CON: 14.5 \u00b1 0.6, UN: 14.69 \u00b1 0.6; P = 0.8), or the sex ratio (male:female) (CON: 1.09 \u00b1 0.1, n = 23, UN: 1.3 \u00b1 0.2, n = 16; P = 0.3). Neonatal UN females had significantly elevated serum insulin levels compared to CON (P = 0.01, Supplemental Figure 2C ), although serum leptin levels were similar between groups (CON: 0.6 ng/ml \u00b1 0.2, n = 6, UN: 0.7 ng/ml \u00b1 0.2, n = 5; P = 0.7). Neonatal glucose levels were similar between groups (Supplemental Figure 2D ), as were brain:body weight ratios (CON: 0.039 g \u00b1 0.001, n = 22, UN: 0.04 g \u00b1 0.001, n = 15; P = 0.5).",
  "correct_citation": {
